/p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>55</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>55</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>88</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30780,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In resultant solution after addition of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math>&nbsp;to the basic buffer:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>08</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mrow><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mi>Cl</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><msubsup><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo></msubsup></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn></math></p><p>Using Henderson-Hasselbach equation:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pOH</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>log</mi><mfrac><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msubsup><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo></msubsup></mfenced><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>745</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>log</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>08</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>745</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>log</mi><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>745</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>477</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>301</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pOH</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>921</mn></math><br />We know,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>pH</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>079</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30819,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2.22</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>18</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>18</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>4.86</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>29</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math><mi>C</mi><mi>r</mi><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>O</mi><mi>H</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>→</mo><mi>C</mi><msup><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>O</mi><msup><mrow></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>  <br/><math><msub><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>s</mi><mo>.</mo><mi></mi><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>S</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math>  <br/><math><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>s</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>  <br/><math><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi>s</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>27</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>  <br/><math><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>O</mi><msup><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>s</mi></math>  <br/><math><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>27</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>14</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>18</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mi>M</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30841,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CCl</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CCl</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;have vacant <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>-</mo></math>orbital and incomplete octet. So they accept lone pair&nbsp;and act as Lewis acids.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30879,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["not a buffer solution with pH  < 7","not a buffer solution with pH > 7","a buffer solution with pH  < 7","a buffer solution with pH > 7"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":30745,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["reduce to $0.5$","increase to $1.3$","remain same","increase to $2$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{HCl}_{(\\mathrm{aq})} \\mathrm{pH}=1 ;\\left[\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right]=10^{-1}$<br />If equal volume of water is added concentration will become half<br />$\\begin{aligned}& {\\left[\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right]_{\\mathrm{sol}}=\\frac{10^{-1}}{2}} \\\\& \\mathrm{pH}=1.3\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30766,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are correct","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Aqueous solution of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is Basic.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi></math> of salt of weak acid and weak base depends on <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub></math> value of acid and the base forming it.</p><p>Solution is basic if</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo> </mo></math>(weak base) &gt;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub><mo> </mo></math>(weak acid).</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub><mo> </mo></math>(<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>HCO</mi><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></math>)=<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>13</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>)</mo></math>=<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub></math> (Ammonium hydroxide) &gt;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub><mrow></mrow></msub><mo> </mo></math>(Hydrogen carbonate)</p><p>∴ Hence, solution of Ammonium carbonate is basic in nature.</p><p>Hence Both Statement I and Statement II are correct.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30811,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Since <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> is salt of weak acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and weak base <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mi>pka</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>pkb</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>23</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>75</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>24</mn><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>7</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30748,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["0.2 M NaCl solution","20 M HCl solution","10 M HCl solution","Neutral solution"],"answer":1,"solution":"When $10 \\mathrm{ml}, 2 \\mathrm{M} \\mathrm{NaOH}$ solution is added to 20 ml of 1 M HCl solution :<br />$\\mathrm{NaOH}+\\mathrm{HCl} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{NaCl}+\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}$<br />Initial : MV $=2 \\times 0.1 \\quad \\mathrm{MV}=1 \\times 0.2$<br />$=0.2 \\text { mole } \\quad=0.2 \\mathrm{~mole}$<br />Final $0 \\quad 0$<br />$\\therefore$ Resulting solution becomes neutral.<br />Now when 10 mol of above solution is poured into a flask containing 2 mole HCl and made solution 100 ml will distilled water.<br />Molarity of $\\mathrm{HCl}=\\frac{2}{100} \\times 1000=20$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30783,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>14</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>78</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>34</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>pH of a mixture of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;has to calculated</p><p>The number of equivalents of HCl is equal to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>equivalents</mi></math></p><p>The number of equivalents of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;given is equal to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>008</mn></math>&nbsp;equivalents</p><p>Hydrogen ion concentration of the resultant mixture is equal to<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>200</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>400</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mn>600</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow><mn>600</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>600</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>60</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>log</mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>60</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>78</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30821,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["Both assertion and reason are true, and the reason is the correct explanation for the assertion.","Both assertion and reason are false.","Both assertion and reason are true, but the reason is not the correct explanation for the assertion.","Assertion is not true, but reason is true."],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mtext>H</mtext><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mtext>O</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub><mo>&#8652;</mo><msubsup><mtext>H</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mtext>aq</mtext><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mtext>OH</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mtext>aq</mtext><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo></msubsup></math><br /><br />For ionization of <math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>H</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mtext>O:</mtext><mi>&#916;</mi><mtext>H&#62;O</mtext></mrow> </math> <math> <mo>&#8658;</mo> </math>&nbsp;Endothermic on&nbsp;temperature increase reaction shifts forward<br /><br /><math> <mo>&#8658;</mo> </math> both <math> <mrow> <mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>H</mtext> <mtext>+</mtext> </msup> </mrow> </mfenced></mrow> </math> and <math> <mrow> <mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>H</mtext> <mtext>-</mtext> </msup> </mrow> </mfenced></mrow> </math> increase<br /><br /><math> <mo>&#8658;</mo> </math> pH &amp; pOH decreases.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30862,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$4.1 \\times 10^{-5} \\mathrm{M}$","$5.1 \\times 10^{-5} \\mathrm{M}$","$8.1 \\times 10^{-8} \\mathrm{M}$","$8.1 \\times 10^{-7} \\mathrm{M}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{Ba}\\left(\\mathrm{NO}_3\\right)_2+\\mathrm{CaCO}_3 \\rightarrow \\mathrm{BaCO}_3+2 \\mathrm{NaNO}_3 \\\\\n& \\text { Here }\\left[\\mathrm{CO}_3^{-2}\\right]=\\left[\\mathrm{Na}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3\\right]=10^{-4} \\mathrm{M} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}=\\left[\\mathrm{Ba}^{+2}\\right]\\left[\\mathrm{CO}_3^{-2}\\right] \\Rightarrow 5.1 \\times 10^{-9}=\\left[\\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}\\right]\\left(10^{-4}\\right) \\Rightarrow\\left[\\mathrm{Ba}^{+2}\\right]=5.1 \\times 10^{-5}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nAt this value, just precipitation starts.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":30827,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math><mn>4.65</mn></math>","<math><mn>2.65</mn></math>","<math><mn>4.35</mn></math>","<math><mn>5.35</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math> is a salt of a strong acid and a weak base.<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">w</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>logC</mi></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>14</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">log</mi></mrow><mo>&#8289;</mo><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mrow></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>-</mo><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">log</mi></mrow><mo>&#8289;</mo><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>-</mo><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">log</mi></mrow><mo>&#8289;</mo><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mrow></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>-</mo><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">log</mi></mrow><mo>&#8289;</mo><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>10.7</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>5.35</mn></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30863,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["iv $ < $ ii $ < $ iii $ < $ i","ii $ < $ iii $ < i < $ iv","i $ < $ iii $ < $ ii $ < $ iv","iii $ < $ i $ < $ iv $ < $ ii"],"answer":2,"solution":"(iv) $>$ (ii) $>$ (iii) $>$ (i)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":30746,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned}<br />& \\mathrm{pH}=10 \\\\<br>& \\mathrm{pOH}=4 \\\\<br>& {\\left[\\mathrm{OH}^{-}\\right]=10^{-4}}<br />\\end{aligned}$<br />no. of moles of $\\mathrm{OH}^{-}=10^{-4}$<br />no. of moles of $\\operatorname{Mg}(\\mathrm{OH})_2=\\frac{10^{-4}}{2}=5 \\times 10^{-5}$<br />$\\text { mass of } \\begin{aligned}<br />\\mathrm{Mg}(\\mathrm{OH})_2 & =5 \\times 10^{-5} \\times 58 \\times 10^3 \\mathrm{mg} \\\\<br>& =2.9<br />\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30801,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>(1) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MeOH</mi></math> is suitable indicator for titration of strong acid and weak base.<br />(2) Acetic acid is weak acid and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;strong base. Phenolphthalein is suitable indicator for titration of weak acid and strong base.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30796,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Bi</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;will get dissociated as:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Bi</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#8652;</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>Bi</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p>Here,</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi>sp</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>108</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>5</mn></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi>sp</mi></msub><mn>108</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mfrac bevelled=\"true\"><mn>1</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>08</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>73</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mn>108</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mfrac bevelled=\"true\"><mn>1</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mol</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30734,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$0.1$ M","$9.53 \\times 10^{-6}$ M","$8.1 \\times 10^{-8}$ M","$1.0 \\times 10^{-13}$ M"],"answer":2,"solution":"Given:<br>Weak dibasic acid $H_2A$ with $K_{a1} = 8.1 \\times 10^{-8}$ and $K_{a2} = 1.0 \\times 10^{-13}$<br>Initial concentration: $[H_2A]_0 = 0.1\\text{ M}$<br>The solution also contains $0.1\\text{ M HCl}$, which dissociates completely to give $[H^+]_0 = 0.1\\text{ M}$.<br><br>The main source of $HA^-$ is the first dissociation:<br>$H_2A \\rightleftharpoons H^+ + HA^-$<br><br>Let $x$ be the amount of $H_2A$ that dissociates. Then at equilibrium:<br>$[H_2A] = 0.1 - x$<br>$[H^+] = 0.1 + x$<br>$[HA^-] = x$<br><br>Applying the equilibrium expression:<br>$K_{a1} = \\dfrac{[H^+][HA^-]}{[H_2A]}$<br><br>$8.1 \\times 10^{-8} = \\dfrac{(0.1 + x)(x)}{0.1 - x}$<br><br>Since $K_{a1}$ is very small and the common $H^+$ ion from HCl suppresses dissociation, $x \\ll 0.1$. Hence:<br>$0.1 - x \\approx 0.1$ and $0.1 + x \\approx 0.1$<br><br>$8.1 \\times 10^{-8} \\approx \\dfrac{(0.1)(x)}{0.1} = x$<br><br>Therefore:<br>$[HA^-] = x = 8.1 \\times 10^{-8}\\text{ M}$<br><br>The second dissociation ($K_{a2} = 1.0 \\times 10^{-13}$) is negligible compared to the first, so the $HA^-$ consumed in that step is insignificant.<br><br>Hence, the correct option is $(3)\\ 8.1 \\times 10^{-8}\\text{ M}$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30815,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable equalrows=\"true\" equalcolumns=\"true\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>AB</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><mover><mo>&#8652;</mo><mrow/></mover></mtd><mtd><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mtd><mtd><mo>+</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd/><mtd/><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mtd><mtd/><mtd><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi>sp</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.20</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>11</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>So solubility&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi>mol</mi><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30772,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>For the insoluble salt barium sulphate, sulphate ion added is the common ion. Due to the common&nbsp;ion effect the solubility of barium sulphate decreases. Let us assume solubility of barium sulphate is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8652;</mo><munder><msup><mi>Ba</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></munder><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><munder><msubsup><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munder><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munder><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munder><mo>&#10230;</mo><munder><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munder><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><munder><msubsup><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munder><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi>SP</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msup><mi>Ba</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mfenced><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msubsup><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></mfenced></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>233</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>gL</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30738,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"For the weak acid dissociation $HA \\rightleftharpoons H^+ + A^-$ with pKa = 4<br>We have Ka = 10⁻⁴.<br>For a 10 mM (0.01 M) solution where the degree of dissociation is negligible with respect to unity, the concentration of HA remains approximately 0.01 M.<br>The equilibrium expression gives<br>$Ka = \\frac{[H^+]^2}{[HA]}$<br>Substituting: $10^{-4} = \\frac{[H^+]^2}{0.01}$, which yields $[H^+]^2 = 10^{-6}$, so $[H^+] = 10^{-3}$ M.<br>Therefore, pH = $-\\log(10^{-3}) = 3$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30794,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Concentration of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math>&nbsp;given is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>001</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>001</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi>OH</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>log</mi><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>log</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>-</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi>OH</mi></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>11</mn></math></p><p>Hence, the&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msup></math>&nbsp;of the given solution of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math>&nbsp;is 11.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30816,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mi>pH</mi></math> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mi>MHCl</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi></math> of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mi>MNaOH</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi></math> of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><msub><mi>MCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COONa</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mn>7</mn></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi></math> of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mi>MNaCl</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn></math><br />So the order of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p>So the order of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pOH</mi><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30756,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ItBS9WwKoHR18vEQ2JbILXjS6Mz4jX2mjo6IZbZs8X0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n\n\nGiven, $\\mathrm{P}^{\\mathrm{H}}=9 \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{P}^{\\mathrm{OH}}=5 \\Rightarrow[\\stackrel{\\ominus}{\\mathrm{OH}}]=10^{-5} \\mathrm{M}$\nNow, $\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{b}}=\\frac{\\left[\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{NH}_3^{+}\\right][\\stackrel{\\ominus}{\\mathrm{O}} \\mathrm{H}]}{\\left[\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{NH}_2\\right]}$\n$\\Rightarrow K_{\\mathrm{b}}=\\frac{10^{-5} \\times 10^{-5}}{10^{-3}}=10^{-7}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30842,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pb</mi><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Al</mi><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi>CN</mi></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mtext>CH</mtext><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COOK</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Salt of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pb</mi><msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></math><br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Weak base&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Weak acid</p><p><br />Salt of<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;</mtext><mi>Al</mi><msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>HCN</mi></math><br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Weak base&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;Weak acid</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Salt of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi><msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math><br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; Weak base&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;Strong acid<br /><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/266699_1.jpg\" style=\"width: 370px; height: 54px;\" /><br /><br />Hence, the nature of the solution is basic.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30776,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The number of millimoles = <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Molarity</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Volume</mi></math> in&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>mL</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math>&nbsp;produce one and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;produce two&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;ions respectively.</p><p>Total milimoles of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>600</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>400</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>14</mn></math><br />Thus, moles of hydrogen ion:<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>14</mn><mn>1000</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>pH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>log</mi><mo>[</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>]</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>log</mi><mo>[</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>]</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>pH</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>log</mi><mn>14</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>86</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>186</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30807,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>ClF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Lewis base: Chemical species which has capability to donate electron pair.</p><p>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>SF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>ClF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> central atom (i.e. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Cl</mi></math>)<br />having lone pair therefore act as Lewis base.</p><p>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>,</mo></math>&nbsp;central atom <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mfenced></math> does not have lone pair therefore does not act as Lewis base.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30817,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Amount of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> in one liter of solution <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo></math> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Mole</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>{</mo><mi>pKa</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>logC</mi><mo>}</mo></math></p><p>For a weak acid solution</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>{</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>}</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30856,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$1.40 \\times 10^{-9}$","$0.14 \\times 10^{-9}$","$140 \\times 10^{-9}$","$14.0 \\times 10^{-9}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{PbI}_2 \\leftrightharpoons \\mathrm{Pb}^{++}+2 \\mathrm{I}^{-}$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\nK_{\\text {sp }}= & s \\times(2 s)^2=4 s^3 \\\\\n& =4 \\times\\left(\\frac{0.7}{461.2}\\right)^3=14.0 \\times 10^{-9}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (26 May Online)","image":null},{"id":30850,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{I}^{-} < \\mathrm{F}^{-} < \\mathrm{HS}^{-} < \\mathrm{NH}_2^{-}$","$\\mathrm{HS}^{-} < \\mathrm{NH}_2^{-} < \\mathrm{F}^{-} < \\mathrm{I}^{-}$","$\\mathrm{F}^{-} < \\mathrm{I}^{-} < \\mathrm{NH}_2^{-} < \\mathrm{HS}^{-}$","$\\mathrm{NH}_2^{-} < \\mathrm{HS}^{-} < \\mathrm{I}^{-} < \\mathrm{F}^{-}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"The species with the greatest proton affinity will be the strongest base, and its conjugate acid will be the weakest acid. The weakest acid will have the smallest value of $\\mathrm{K}_a$. Since $\\mathrm{HI}$ is a stronger acid than $\\mathrm{HF}$ which is a stronger acid than $\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{S}$, a partial order of proton affinity is \n$\\mathrm{I}^{-} < \\mathrm{F}^{-} < \\mathrm{HS}^{-}$\nSince $\\mathrm{NH}_3$ is a very weak acid, $\\mathrm{NH}_2^{-}$must be a very strong base. Therefore the correct order of proton affinity is\n$\\mathrm{I}^{-} < \\mathrm{F}^{-} < \\mathrm{HS}^{-} < \\mathrm{NH}_2^{-}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null}]